---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import {vaultSidebar} from '../../../data/vault-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Getting Started with Vault" sidebar={vaultSidebar}
            description="Core Vault concepts end-to-end: entities, wrappers, cursors, and backends">

    <h1>Getting Started</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Vault is the shared persistence foundation underneath Karango and Monko.
        This page walks through the core concepts you need before choosing a backend.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Define your entity</h2>

    <p>Annotate a data class with <code>@Vault</code>. Your domain model stays free of database concerns.</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.Vault

@Vault
data class Article(
    val title: String,
    val body: String,
    val tags: List<String> = emptyList(),
)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>2. The Storable wrappers</h2>

    <p>Vault wraps every entity in one of three types, depending on its lifecycle stage.
        Database metadata lives in the wrapper, never in your data class.</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.New
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.Stored
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.Ref

// Before saving — no database metadata yet
val new: New<Article> = New(Article("Draft", "..."))

// After saving — carries _id, _key, _rev from the database
val stored: Stored<Article> = repo.insert(Article("Hello", "World"))
stored._id    // "articles/abc123"
stored._key   // "abc123"
stored()      // Article(title="Hello", body="World")

// A lazy reference — resolves on first access
val ref: Ref<Article> = stored.asRef`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>3. Working with Stored</h2>

    <p>Use <code>modify</code> to create an updated copy that preserves database identity,
        or <code>transform</code> to change the value type entirely.</p>

    <Code code={`// Access the value
val article: Article = stored()

// Create a modified copy — same _id, _key, _rev
val updated: Stored<Article> = stored.modify { it.copy(title = "New Title") }

// Transform to a different type
val titleOnly: Stored<String> = stored.transform { it.title }

// Replace the value outright
val replaced: Stored<Article> = stored.withValue(Article("Replaced", "Content"))`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>4. Resolving values</h2>

    <p><code>suspend fun resolve()</code> and its shorthand <code>suspend operator fun invoke()</code> work
        uniformly on all Storable types. For <code>Stored</code> and <code>New</code>, resolution is instant.
        For <code>Ref</code>, it may suspend to load from the database.</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.Storable

suspend fun printTitle(storable: Storable<Article>) {
    // Both forms are equivalent:
    val a1: Article = storable.resolve()
    val a2: Article = storable()  // shorthand

    println(a1.title)
}

// Works the same for any wrapper type
printTitle(new)     // instant
printTitle(stored)  // instant
printTitle(ref)     // may suspend to load from DB, then cached`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>5. Cursors</h2>

    <p><code>Cursor&lt;T&gt;</code> wraps a Kotlin Flow and provides suspend-friendly collection operations.
        Repository queries return cursors, so you can stream results lazily or collect them all at once.</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.Cursor
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.filter
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.map
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.vault.firstOrNull

val cursor: Cursor<Stored<Article>> = repo.findAll()

// Collect everything
val all: List<Stored<Article>> = cursor.toList()

// Transform
val titles: List<String> = cursor.map { it().title }

// Filter
val tagged: List<Stored<Article>> = cursor.filter { "kotlin" in it().tags }

// First match
val first: Stored<Article>? = cursor.firstOrNull { it().title == "Hello" }`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>6. Choose your backend</h2>

    <p>Vault defines the abstractions. To actually persist data, pick a backend and follow its getting-started
        guide.</p>

    <div class="not-prose mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-4">
        <a href="/ultra/karango/getting-started"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Karango (ArangoDB) &rarr;
        </a>
        <a href="/ultra/monko/getting-started"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Monko (MongoDB) &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

    <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
        <a href="/ultra/vault/storable"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Storable Hierarchy &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
